menu.description: Perfecting our Chun family recipe for our Baked Manapua bread took us 10 years and is a treasured secret. We are also proud of our char siu filling, which we cook at high heat to add a bit of char and a unique flavor that can only come from a wok. Our Baked Manapua helped to put us on the map and continues to be an island favorite.
Steamed Manapua lovers argue that this product is better than our Baked Manapua. Probably because our pillowy soft steamed bread rivals that of our baked bread. Try one of each and you be the judge!
Our popular char siu filling is also available in a mini size!
One of our original assorted fillings, this manapua is filled with stringy mozzarella cheese, pepperoni, and made-from-scratch tomato sauce.
We marinate our pork in a fiery Szechuan sauce and combine it with wok seared shiitake mushrooms and chilis to give you something with a little more pep!
This filling started off as a monthly special but was so popular we added it to our permanent menu. We use premium Japanese curry and fresh herbs to give this filling its bold flavor.
Red azuki beans have been an island favorite for all sorts of sweet treats. Try it in our manapua for something different!
A classic Chinese sausage rolled in a fresh bun that is steamed until fluffy soft.
This one's a little bit sweet and a little bit savory, with just the right amount of garlic, making this flavor popular for years.
We never settle for anything less than the best, which is why we only use 100% beef hot dogs.
This plate comes with up to two choices of starch and two choices of entrees.
For those of you who can't handle the bigger Plate Lunch, the Bowl is perfect. You can choose one starch and one entree choice!
One of our most popular menu items, Chun Wah pork hash is a generous serving of our one-of-a-kind pork filling covered in a wrapper that we make from scratch.
This classic Chinese dim sum item combines daikon, minced charisiu, dried shrimp, and seasonings in a steamed chewy wrapper.
Big, crispy, crunchy, and stuffed with our signature pork filling. An absolute customer favorite, Chun Wah kau gee is a cut above the rest.
Available in white or 9-layer varieties, these desserts have been popular since back back back in the day.

The flaky crust on our tarts takes more effort to make but we think they're worth the time. The custard is sweet and creamy without being too rich. We have these available on Fridays, Saturdays, and Sundays, but be sure to call ahead to check availability.

A savory Hawaiian stew made with braised beef chuck, sauted onions, ginger and taro leaves that have been slow cooked until tender and packed with umami flavor.

Pork butt slow cooked and smoked for twelve hours achieving a fall off the bone tenderness that is then shredded and seasoned with Hawaiian sea salt. A dish that no Hawaiian menu would be complete without.

Thinly sliced octopus made tender in a rich and creamy coconut milk combined with slowly cooked taro leaves and seasoned with Hawaiian sea salt. A local favorite looked forward to at every Hawaiian gathering.
A delicious chicken and rice noodle dish served in a ginger and chicken broth. A simple, elegant dish and a perfect alternative to our beef and pork selections.
A traditional Hawaiian dish consisting of a generous amount of pork and a touch of butter fish that is wrapped and steamed in taro leaves. A rich and flavorful medley of greens and protein.

A refreshing fern salad with julienne onions and diced tomatoes garnished with dried shrimp and served with a sweet soy and ginger sauce. The perfect item for a vegan diet, just ask to hold the shrimp.
A traditional Hawaiian side dish of diced tomatoes, onion, green onion and salt cured salmon that no Hawaiian plate would be complete without.
Haupia is a light and fluffy coconut dessert with a consistency similar to custard. A true classic served on many Hawaiian menus.

Poi is a starch derived from the taro root and has been the staple of the Hawaiian diet since the beginning. The taro root is steamed and either milled, or pounded and mixed with water to a smooth consistency and pairs well with any Hawaiian dish.

Short grain white rice has also become a staple of the Hawaiian diet since its arrival from Asia many years ago. Contemporarily white rice has been served along side many local and Hawaiian favorites.
Our limeade is the perfect drink to beat the heat and is made in house with fresh squeezed lime juice.
Mamaki is a red Hawaiian tea that is brewed fresh in house with Mamaki leaves and lemon grass.
Mamaki is a red Hawaiian tea that is brewed fresh in house with Mamaki leaves and lemon grass.
Awa is a very traditional and both ceremonial and social drink that can have a relaxing effect when consumed.

An ode to the classic Vics 44 Mai Tai, featuring local Ko Hana Kea Agricole rhum, fresh lime, orgeat, orange liqueur, and topped with El Dorado 15yr aged rum.

This cocktail honors the goddess Pele and allows us to recognize all the beauty that surrounds us thanks to her creation. Created with local Kohana rum, pineapple juice, strawberry puree, lime juice and grenadine.
A beverage that praises the wonderous ocean colors that surround us. This cocktail is made up of empress gin, pink lemonade, blue curacao and crme de violette.

Makai in Hawaiian culture stands for the direction that is towards the ocean. In enjoying this cocktail we hope to bring that refreshing feeling one gets from being near the ocean. This cocktail is made of tequila, con treau, lime juice and mango puree.

The SS Mariposa was Matsons second luxury liner and part of their signature, White Fleet - she voyaged throughout the Pacific and Tasman Sea. To celebrate these journeys, weve combined El Tequileno Repo sado tequila, Kohana Koho Agricole rhum, macnut or geat, poblano liqueur, and fresh local juices to harken back those luxurious and exotic Pan-Pacific days.

In honor of Mary Robins song, Royal Hawaiian Hotel which was played late into the evening on opening night, February 1, 1927 this elegant yet boozy concoction will ease the mind with tropical call backs to one of the grandest soirees the Pacific has known. Prepared with local Pau Maui vodka, Aperol, chamomile syrup, lemon juice, and finished with club soda.

The final luxury liner built by Matson, christened SS Lurline, in 1932, Lurline was used for express passage from San Francisco to Honolulu. The cool and breezy Lurline Lemonade is reminiscent of days at sea and nights on the promenade. Made tall with Fid Street gin, dried lavender, lemon, and club soda.

Every evening at 6pm, The Royal Hawaiian bell tower chimes to signify dining hour has begun. This evening, treat yourself to an espresso martini to get the festivities started Absolut vodka, Kahlua, local espresso, served chilled and up.
